<div class="page">
  <div class="chapter-title">Chapter 1<br>Introduction</div>
  <p class="justify">
    This chapter presents the background, motivation, objectives, feasibility, identified gaps,
    and expected outcomes of the Quiz Master project. It establishes why the project is relevant
    in the context of digital learning, assessment automation, and mobile software engineering.
  </p>

  <h2>Introduction</h2>
  <p class="justify">
    Quiz Master is a role-based mobile examination and practice platform built with Flutter and Firebase.
    The project addresses a common academic need: teachers or administrators require a structured way
    to configure quizzes, control exam policies, manage question banks, and monitor student progress,
    while students need a simple and responsive platform to practice, attend exams, review results, and
    track their performance over time. The system provides separate workflows for admin and student users
    and integrates authentication, real-time cloud data management, and profile personalization.
  </p>
  <p class="justify">
    The project solves the problem of fragmented classroom assessment by combining quiz delivery, result
    generation, leaderboard tracking, progress visualization, and profile management in a single mobile-first
    environment. By using Flutter, the same codebase can support Android, iOS, web, macOS, and other desktop
    platforms with a consistent interface.
  </p>

  <h2>Motivation</h2>
  <p class="justify">
    The primary motivation behind this project is to develop a practical mobile application that demonstrates
    the full lifecycle of a modern software product: requirement analysis, UI design, role-based access control,
    cloud integration, testing, and deployment readiness. Traditional academic quiz systems are often either
    too static, too web-dependent, or not tailored for small-scale classroom administration. Quiz Master was
    motivated by the need for a cleaner, more controllable, and more student-friendly solution.
  </p>
  <p class="justify">
    From a learning perspective, the project also provided the opportunity to apply mobile application concepts
    such as reactive UI updates, asynchronous programming, Firebase-based backend services, image selection,
    data modeling, and result analytics. The system benefits the developer by translating classroom concepts into
    a working software product and benefits end users by simplifying assessment management.
  </p>

  <h2>Objectives</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>To design and implement a role-based quiz and examination portal using Flutter.</li>
    <li>To provide secure user authentication and cloud-backed profile management using Firebase services.</li>
    <li>To allow administrators to create, manage, and remove quiz questions from a centralized question bank.</li>
    <li>To allow administrators to configure exam title, duration, question count, attempt limits, practice mode, and review behavior.</li>
    <li>To enable students to attend timed exams and topic-based practice sessions from a single interface.</li>
    <li>To generate immediate score summaries, answer reviews, and AI-style recommendations after quiz completion.</li>
    <li>To visualize progress using attempt history, subject-wise performance, and leaderboard data.</li>
    <li>To support profile customization, including profile information and profile picture management.</li>
    <li>To validate the application through static analysis and automated Flutter test cases.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Feasibility Study</h2>
  <p class="justify">
    Similar systems already exist in the educational technology domain. Learning management systems such as Moodle
    provide assessment modules but are often institution-heavy and require more administrative configuration than
    small classes need. Lightweight quiz systems such as Google Forms support quick testing but offer limited role-based
    exam governance and weak analytics for subject-wise performance. Gamified platforms such as Quizizz and Kahoot
    are effective for engagement but may not align with stricter classroom exam control and custom institutional needs [1][2][3].
  </p>
  <p class="justify">
    From a technical perspective, the feasibility of building Quiz Master is high because Flutter provides a mature
    cross-platform UI toolkit, while Firebase offers ready-made services for authentication, cloud data synchronization,
    and media storage. The repo confirms the practical feasibility: the application initializes Firebase, routes users
    through an app shell, stores questions, attempts, settings, and user profiles in cloud collections, and already passes
    analysis and automated test checks.
  </p>

  <h2>Gap Analysis</h2>
  <p class="justify">
    Existing systems often separate content management, testing, analytics, and user personalization into different tools.
    Quiz Master addresses this gap by combining them in a single mobile application. Another gap is the lack of lightweight,
    mobile-first assessment apps that offer both administrator control and student autonomy. Many existing tools either focus
    on large enterprise learning platforms or purely casual quiz interaction. Quiz Master occupies a middle ground by providing
    structured exam control, practice flexibility, and progress analytics in a compact academic product.
  </p>
  <p class="justify">
    The current work also improves on earlier offline or local-only approaches by using Firebase Auth, Cloud Firestore, and
    Firebase Storage. This removes device-only limitations, allows account continuity across sessions, and supports profile picture
    features that require real media handling.
  </p>

  <h2>Project Outcome</h2>
  <p class="justify">
    The project outcome is a functional, multi-screen mobile application that supports two types of users: administrators and
    students. Administrators can manage questions, configure exams, observe leaderboards, and review overall progress. Students
    can create accounts, sign in, edit profiles, upload profile pictures, practice by subject, attend timed exams, and receive
    instant feedback through result summaries and AI-style recommendations.
  </p>
  <p class="justify">
    A secondary outcome is academic: the project demonstrates practical application of software engineering principles such as
    modular architecture, data modeling, validation, cross-platform UI development, and testing. It also produces a reusable
    codebase that can be extended into a more complete institutional learning product.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="page">
  <div class="chapter-title">Chapter 2<br>Proposed Methodology/Architecture</div>
  <p class="justify">
    This chapter describes the requirement analysis, design specification, system overview, proposed architecture,
    user interface design, and overall project plan used to build Quiz Master. It translates the project goals into
    concrete software structure and implementation strategy.
  </p>

  <h2>Requirement Analysis &amp; Design Specification</h2>
  <h3>Functional Requirements</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>User registration and login with Firebase Authentication.</li>
    <li>Role-based routing for admin and student dashboards.</li>
    <li>Admin-controlled exam settings and question bank management.</li>
    <li>Student practice mode and timed exam mode.</li>
    <li>Leaderboard, attempt history, result review, and progress visualization.</li>
    <li>User profile editing with image selection and profile picture saving.</li>
    <li>Cloud data synchronization for users, questions, attempts, and settings.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Non-Functional Requirements</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Responsive and clean UI across Flutter-supported platforms.</li>
    <li>Reliable asynchronous data handling with clear error feedback.</li>
    <li>Maintainable architecture with separated controller, models, services, screens, and widgets.</li>
    <li>Security through authenticated access and Firebase rules for Firestore and Storage.</li>
    <li>Testability through automated widget and controller tests.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p class="justify">
    The application starts in <strong>main.dart</strong>, where Firebase is initialized using generated platform options.
    After startup, <strong>QuizMasterApp</strong> creates an <strong>AppController</strong> and passes it to the <strong>AppShell</strong>.
    The app shell works as a gateway. It shows a loading screen during initialization, an error screen if backend access fails,
    an authentication screen when no user is signed in, and the appropriate dashboard when a user is authenticated.
  </p>

  <h2>Proposed Methodology / System Design</h2>
  <p class="justify">
    The system follows a layered design inspired by MVC and repository-based patterns. Presentation logic is contained in screens
    and widgets, state coordination is handled by the controller, and Firebase communication is isolated in repository/service code.
    This reduces coupling and makes the code easier to extend and test.
  </p>

  <div class="figure-box">
    <p><strong>Presentation Layer:</strong> AuthScreen, HomeScreen, AdminDashboardScreen, QuizScreen, ResultScreen, ProfileScreen</p>
    <p><strong>State Layer:</strong> AppShell, AppController, ChangeNotifier-based updates</p>
    <p><strong>Repository Layer:</strong> AppRepository interface and FirebaseAppRepository implementation</p>
    <p><strong>Cloud Layer:</strong> Firebase Auth, Cloud Firestore, Firebase Storage</p>
    <p><strong>Model Layer:</strong> UserModel, QuestionModel, ExamAttempt, ExamSettings</p>
    <p><strong>Utility Layer:</strong> AI Analyzer, progress visualization, shared avatar widget</p>
  </div>
  <p class="caption">Figure 2.1: Simplified architecture of the Quiz Master system</p>

  <p class="justify">
    The controller listens to Firebase authentication state and then subscribes to cloud streams for users, questions, attempts,
    and settings. This ensures the UI is updated reactively whenever backend data changes. The repository handles login, signup,
    profile updates, image uploads, question management, settings updates, and attempt persistence. The design also allows future
    replacement of the data source by keeping the controller dependent on an abstract repository contract.
  </p>

  <h3>Core Data Flow</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>User launches the app and Firebase initializes.</li>
    <li>Authentication state determines whether the user sees login/signup or a dashboard.</li>
    <li>After authentication, the controller loads Firestore-backed app data.</li>
    <li>Admin updates or student attempts generate writes to Firestore and trigger UI refresh through streams.</li>
    <li>Quiz completion generates local analysis results and then stores them as an attempt record.</li>
    <li>Profile updates optionally upload a photo to Firebase Storage and save the returned URL in the user document.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>UI Design</h2>
  <p class="justify">
    The UI design uses Material 3 principles with a soft indigo-based color scheme, rounded cards, generous whitespace, and
    readable typography through Google Fonts. The authentication screen is designed to be simple and form-centric, while the
    dashboards highlight actions and analytics. The admin dashboard emphasizes control and monitoring, whereas the student
    dashboard emphasizes readiness, motivation, and guided practice.
  </p>
  <p class="justify">
    Specific UI patterns include segmented buttons for login/signup and user role selection, cards for summarized metrics, filter
    chips for topic-based practice preparation, circular avatar displays for profile identity, and progress bars/charts for academic
    visualization. The recent profile picture feature extends this design by allowing users to pick, preview, change, and remove an
    image from the profile screen with a consistent avatar widget across the application.
  </p>

