</div>

<div class="page">
  <div class="chapter-title">Chapter 3<br>Implementation and Results</div>
  <p class="justify">
    This chapter presents how the system was implemented, how the major modules work together, and what results were obtained
    from the completed application. It also analyzes performance and discusses the practical behavior of the current version.
  </p>

  <h2>Implementation</h2>
  <p class="justify">
    The frontend was implemented in Flutter using a screen-based structure under the <strong>lib/screens</strong> directory.
    The app includes separate screens for authentication, admin dashboard, student home dashboard, quiz interaction, result
    display, and profile management. Common UI elements such as progress visualization and user avatars are placed in reusable
    widgets. Application-wide navigation and state-driven view switching are managed through the app shell and controller.
  </p>
  <p class="justify">
    On the backend side, Firebase services were integrated through a repository implementation. Firebase Authentication manages
    account creation, login, logout, and basic user identity. Cloud Firestore stores user profiles, question banks, settings,
    and attempt histories. Firebase Storage is used for profile image upload and retrieval. Firestore rules and storage rules are
    included in the project to align data access with authenticated ownership and admin control.
  </p>

  <h3>Implemented Modules</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Authentication Module:</strong> Sign up, login, role assignment, and connection-aware routing.</li>
    <li><strong>Admin Module:</strong> Question bank CRUD operations, exam control settings, student progress overview.</li>
    <li><strong>Student Module:</strong> Topic selection, practice mode, exam mode, attempt history, and leaderboard.</li>
    <li><strong>Result Analysis Module:</strong> Score calculation, subject-wise aggregation, and AI-style recommendations.</li>
    <li><strong>Profile Module:</strong> Editable user profile fields, profile photo upload, change, and removal.</li>
    <li><strong>Testing Module:</strong> Widget and controller tests for key behavior such as signup, routing, and attempt limits.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Performance Analysis</h2>
  <p class="justify">
    The application is lightweight from an algorithmic perspective. Core quiz scoring requires a single pass over the selected
    question list, resulting in a time complexity of <strong>O(n)</strong> where <em>n</em> is the number of questions. Subject-wise
    analysis and answer review generation also operate in linear time over the question set. Leaderboard generation depends on sorting
    current exam attempts, which has <strong>O(m log m)</strong> complexity where <em>m</em> is the number of relevant attempts.
  </p>
  <p class="justify">
    From a practical runtime perspective, Flutter provides smooth UI rendering, while Firebase handles cloud synchronization and
    authentication asynchronously. The project does not currently include formal benchmark instrumentation, but code-level validation
    confirms operational stability. Static analysis shows no issues, and automated tests verify core user flow correctness. The recent
    architecture shift from local storage to Firebase also improves consistency across sessions and platforms.
  </p>

  <table>
    <tr>
      <th>Metric</th>
      <th>Observation</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Static Analysis</td>
      <td><code>flutter analyze</code> completed successfully with no issues in the final validated state.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Automated Tests</td>
      <td><code>flutter test</code> passed 5 key tests covering authentication flow, signup, exam attempts, and settings behavior.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Scoring Complexity</td>
      <td>Linear, O(n), over total questions in an attempt.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Leaderboard Complexity</td>
      <td>Sorting-based, O(m log m), over current exam attempts.</td>
    </tr>
  </table>

  <h2>Results and Discussion</h2>
  <p class="justify">
    The final result is a working mobile application that demonstrates a complete educational assessment workflow. The admin can
    configure the system and question bank without modifying source code. Students can create accounts, join the platform, take
    practice sessions or exams, and receive immediate, meaningful feedback. The profile module extends usability by supporting
    personalization and identity display.
  </p>
  <p class="justify">
    A particularly strong outcome is the integration of analytics into a beginner-friendly mobile system. Rather than displaying only
    a raw score, the application translates attempt data into suggestions and subject insights. This increases the educational value of
    the app. Another successful outcome is the architecture itself: screens, controller logic, models, repository abstraction, and cloud
    services are cleanly separated, which makes the project easier to maintain and improve.
  </p>
  <p class="justify">
    The project also reveals realistic deployment considerations. For example, Firebase configuration, Firestore rules, Storage setup,
    and platform-specific permissions such as macOS network entitlements are essential for real-world mobile engineering. This makes the
    project especially valuable as a lab exercise because it captures both coding and operational aspects of software development.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="page">
  <div class="chapter-title">Chapter 4<br>Engineering Standards and Mapping</div>
  <p class="justify">
    This chapter evaluates the project from broader engineering perspectives including social impact, sustainability, ethics,
    project management, program outcome mapping, complex problem characteristics, and engineering activity classifications.
  </p>

  <h2>Impact on Society, Environment and Sustainability</h2>

  <h3>Impact on Life</h3>
  <p class="justify">
    Quiz Master improves academic life by making classroom assessment more organized and accessible. Students receive immediate feedback,
    topic-focused practice, and a clearer understanding of their strengths and weaknesses. Administrators or teachers save time by using
    a centralized platform instead of manually handling separate quiz tools, spreadsheets, and paper records.
  </p>

  <h3>Impact on Society &amp; Environment</h3>
  <p class="justify">
    The project supports digital transformation in education by reducing dependence on paper-based quizzes and result processing. In a
    broader social sense, it encourages technology adoption in assessment workflows and contributes to smarter educational management.
    Using a cross-platform mobile stack also increases reach because the same system can support multiple device types. Environmentally,
    digital quiz delivery can reduce paper consumption, printing cost, and repeated administrative handling.
  </p>

  <h3>Ethical Aspects</h3>
  <p class="justify">
    Ethical considerations include protecting user identity, restricting unauthorized access, and preventing unfair administrative actions.
    The project addresses these through authenticated access, role separation, and backend rule design. Profile pictures and personal details
    are user-owned information, so access is constrained by account identity. Ethical development also requires transparency, so the system
    clearly distinguishes practice mode from exam mode and visibly communicates quiz conditions such as attempt limits and answer review policy.
  </p>

  <h3>Sustainability Plan</h3>
  <p class="justify">
    The system is designed for long-term maintainability. Flutter enables a single codebase, reducing maintenance duplication. Firebase reduces
    server-management burden for small academic deployments. The repository abstraction allows future replacement or expansion of backend services.
    Additional sustainability measures for future versions include analytics logging, teacher feedback export, stronger storage configuration,
    and institutional deployment procedures.
  </p>

  <h2>Project Management and Team Work</h2>
  <p class="justify">
    This version of the project was prepared as a single-student implementation, so planning, coding, testing, debugging, and documentation were
    coordinated within one workflow. The project still follows structured engineering stages: requirement identification, architecture planning,
    iterative implementation, validation, and reporting. Even in an individual setting, these activities reflect core team-work values such as
    accountability, integration discipline, and milestone-based progress.
  </p>

  <h3>Budget and Revenue Model</h3>
  <table>
    <tr>
      <th>Item</th>
      <th>Primary Budget (BDT)</th>
      <th>Alternate Budget (BDT)</th>
      <th>Rationale</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Development Laptop / Workstation</td>
      <td>0</td>
      <td>60,000</td>
      <td>Primary assumes existing personal machine; alternate assumes new budget laptop purchase.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Internet Connectivity</td>
      <td>1,500</td>
      <td>3,000</td>
      <td>Needed for dependency download, Firebase console setup, and backend testing.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Firebase Services</td>
      <td>0</td>
      <td>5,000</td>
      <td>Primary assumes Spark/free-tier academic use; alternate reserves cost for higher usage or storage growth.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Testing Devices</td>
      <td>0</td>
      <td>15,000</td>
      <td>Primary assumes existing device/emulator access; alternate covers a low-cost physical Android test device.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Documentation and Miscellaneous</td>
      <td>500</td>
      <td>1,500</td>
      <td>Printing, formatting, and project submission preparation.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <th>Total</th>
      <th>2,000</th>
      <th>84,500</th>
      <th>Primary is low-cost student development; alternate reflects a more formal deployment-ready setup.</th>
    </tr>
  </table>
  <p class="justify">
    A suitable revenue model for future commercialization would be an institutional subscription model where schools, coaching centers, or departments
    pay per semester or per active batch. A freemium model could also be used, where small classes use a free version while analytics export, advanced
    reporting, and multi-admin workflows remain premium features.
  </p>

  <h2>Complex Engineering Problem</h2>
  <p class="justify">
    Although Quiz Master is a student lab project, it still represents a complex engineering problem because it combines user management, cloud services,
    data synchronization, UI design, role-based constraints, and assessment logic in one integrated solution. The developer must balance usability,
    security, correctness, scalability, and platform compatibility at the same time.
  </p>

  <h2>Mapping of Program Outcome</h2>
  <p><strong>Table 4.1: Justification of Program Outcomes</strong></p>
  <table>
    <tr>
      <th>PO's</th>
      <th>Justification</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>PO1</td>
      <td>The project applies core computing and engineering knowledge through Flutter application development, Firebase integration, data modeling, and interface construction.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>PO2</td>
      <td>The problem was analyzed in terms of user roles, exam policies, state synchronization, and data consistency, which required structured reasoning and technical decision-making.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>PO3</td>
      <td>The final solution was designed as a practical mobile software product that satisfies real educational needs while maintaining usability, modularity, and deployability.</td>
    </tr>
  </table>

  <h2>Complex Problem Solving</h2>
  <p><strong>Table 4.2: Mapping with complex problem solving</strong></p>
